To install and run Flutter, your development environment must meet these minimum requirements:

    # Operating Systems: Windows 7 SP1 or later (64-bit)

    # Enough Disk Space

    # Tools: Flutter depends on these tools being available in your environment.
        Windows PowerShell 5.0 or newer (this is pre-installed with Windows 10)

        Git for Windows 2.x, with the Use Git from the Windows Command Prompt option.

        If Git for Windows is already installed, make sure you can run git commands from the command prompt or PowerShell.

# get The sdk from https://flutter.dev/docs/get-started/install/windows
# Extract the zip file and place the contained flutter in the desired installation location for the Flutter SDK (Prefer making a new folder dirrectly in C drive)
# Edit environment variables for your account.

Download android studio from here https://developer.android.com/studio/

Dart installation:
    Start Android Studio.
    Open plugin preferences (Configure > Plugins as of v3.6.3.0 or later).
    Select the Flutter plugin and click Install.
    Click Yes when prompted to install the Dart plugin.
    Click Restart when prompted.

set flutter package loaction for android studio to find the right location

You are good to go!

How to run the application:
if you want to see the mobile screens you'll have to change a few things in the code.
To directly see under development screen of one:one type these commands. 
(This was still underdevelopment and you might see 2 3 bugs, but these are resolvable and can be resolved by anyone who knows flutter)
cmds:
    in your project root folder terminal run these cmds:
    
    flutter channel beta
    flutter upgrade
    flutter config --enable-web

   You can run flutter doctor to see and debug any issue with flutter setup.  
   
   run this command to see the output in chrome browser
   flutter run -d chrome

NOTE THAT IF YOU WANT TO SEE ANY OTHER SCREEN YOU'LL HAVE TO CHANGE ROUTE GENERATOR CLASS AND RETURN WIDGETS ACCORDINGLY IN THE WEB HOME
WIDGET.

For any other query reach 
https://flutter.dev/docs/get-started/web
OR
stackoverflow (it has a ton of good answers)
   
   
   
   
   
    
    
    


